data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

**What happened:** In .NET 10 / C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of the old `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based methods, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

**Fix — cast or call explicitly:**

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these forces the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees support.
